Outcome #1: 
The National ODS Consumption Report (HCFC) for 2018 for the country (Form 1), according to the Montreal Protocol, has been prepared and submitted to the Ozone Secretariat. (according to report, country in compliance article). 
 Conducted survey, from September to December 2019, on alternatives to ODS, HFCs, to determine national consumption and a baseline and prepare a set of data that will help the government understand new trends in the import and use of new technologies, including natural refrigerants, such as carbon dioxide, ammonia, hydrocarbons and other gases from the HFC and HFO groups, as well as other technologies such as absorption, natural cooling and heat pumps. This information will provide important data for planning HCFC phase-out processes in relation to alternative technologies that will replace HCFCs and will enable the government to understand the consequences of the Kigali amendment to the Montreal Protocol on HFCs phase-out in Tajikistan; 
- In April 24, 2020 the Letter of Agreement was signed between the United Nations Development Programme and the Committee for Environmental Protection under the Government of the Republic of Tajikistan on the implementation of the project “Complete HCFC Phase-out in the Republic of Tajikistan through introduction of technologies with zero ODP and low GWP”. The main key result of the activities within the reporting period (July 2019 – June 2020) is the development, adaptation, improvement and promotion of legislative and regulatory acts, including standards / rules and instructions on safety and environmental requirements to reduce HCFC consumption in Tajikistan for 2020-2030. A survey of the consumption of HFCs with high GWP has determined the national baseline for the consumption of HFCs in the country, as well as the preparation and submission of legal acts on the ratification of the Kigali Amendment of the Montreal Protocol to the Government of the Republic of Tajikistan. 

Outcome #2: 
The HCFC Project has hired National Legal Consultant to continue the work toward implementation of the recommendations made by International Legislation Expert on improvement of national legislation, normative and regulatory frameworks and standards for the protection of the ozone layer and handling of ODS in Tajikistan. The UNDP HCFC project started the assessment to identify gaps and issue recommendations on the national legislation for protecting the ozone layer, handling of ODS and its alternatives as part of the Complete HCFC Phase Out program by introducing technologies with zero ODP and low GWP in Context of the Kigali amendment of the Montreal Protocol, which improve regulations on handling ODS safety related standards on zero ODP and low GWP; A total of 2 Regulatory acts on Complete HCFC Phase Out and ODS waste disposal and determined the consumption and use of current alternatives to HCFC which included a range of non-ODS options, including natural refrigerant solutions. 

